John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent Scottish schools maintain a curriculum of academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another series of outstanding results to the exams, reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other collective efforts.
With over 30,000 students throughout Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the best level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare pupils for further higher education, career choices and their place in the world as global citizens.
As a field of education able to develop and adopt a custom school curriculum, we note that modern languages continue to be a popular subject and required within schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message will reach his brain.
If you speak to him in his mother tongue, the message will reach his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot trust only English if we want to create trust with people from other countries.
From the results of this year's exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
68% of pupils who studied foreign languages obtained the highest vote.
Data, collected from the 74 SCIS member schools, showed that 72% of students obtained the highest vote with praise in Chinese, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish got the highest vote.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are promoting foreign languages as fundamental skills for children and young people, who will certainly need them in the future.
At present, languages, such as choice of subject, are considered at the same level as STEM (science, technology, technology and mathematics) in the study plans of independent institutions and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the United Kingdom Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that the reasons for the difficulty in covering jobs are attributable in 17% of cases to a lack of language skills.
For this reason language skills are becoming increasingly indispensable in preparing young people for their future careers.
With increasing job opportunities requiring language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if you have learned a second language, you will have an effective advantage in the future with a life competence like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will lead a multilingual person automatically to competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language at a sufficient level to be able to hold a conversation and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%.
For this reason investing in language teaching is so important to children today.
Knowledge of more languages, in particular those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a valid job.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages taught.
Several schools will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the United Kingdom looking at 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with the specialized teaching staff in this area.
Independent Scottish schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills necessary for success, regardless of their future.
It is not possible to deny at this time, in a global trading system, that languages continue to be fundamental to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in teaching.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communicative competences."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence for young people in Scotland.
We have to do this right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
