North Korea absolutely refuses to unilateral disarmament without confidence
The Foreign Minister of North Korea declared to the United Nations on Saturday that the maintenance of sanctions was undermining the country's confidence in the USA, which in these circumstances would absolutely refuse to give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally.
Ri Yong Ho stated at the General Assembly of the world body that North Korea has adopted "significant measures of goodwill" over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the site for nuclear tests and commitment to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see any consistent response from the USA," he said.
"Without confidence in the USA there will be no security in our national security and in these circumstances we absolutely refuse to disarm ourselves unilaterally for the first time."
Although Ri re-uses the lamentation notes concerning Washington's resistance to a "in-phase" denuclearization with which North Korea would be awarded on the basis of gradual actions, his statement was important because he did not completely reject unilateral denuclearization as already done by Pyongyang in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the first absolute meeting between a US president in office and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on 12 June, when Kim undertook to work towards the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula", while Trump promised guarantees to North Korean security.
North Korea has sought a formal end-to-end agreement to the 1950-53 Korean war, but the United States has stated that Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also opposed appeals to ease the strict international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The US insists on the need to "have denuclearization first" and to increase the pressure level with sanctions to achieve their purpose in a coercive manner and even oppose the "war-end declaration," said Ri.
"The idea that sanctions can put us on our knees is an illusion of those who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions is increasing our confidence."
Ri did not refer to programs of a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the US leader announced at the UN at the beginning of the week.
On the other hand, the minister stressed the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If the counterpart to this issue of denuclearization was South Korea and not the USA, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be at this point dead."
But also, the tone of Ri's speech was significantly different from that of last year's speech to the UN General Assembly, when he stated that it was inevitable to target the US territory with North Korea's missiles after "the president of evil" Trump had called Kim a "missile man" engaged in a suicide mission.
Before the United Nations Trump, who last year had threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, he praised Kim for his courage to undertake the course of disarmament, but said that much has to be done and that sanctions will remain in force until North Korea is denuclearized.
On Wednesday Trump said he didn't have a deadline, saying that "if it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia say that the UN Security Council should award Pyongyang for the actions taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo declared Thursday to the UN Security Council: "The respect of the sanctions of the Security Council must continue with force and without exception until complete, final and determined denuclearization is achieved."
The Security Council unanimously supported North Korea's sanctions in 2006 in an attempt to stifle the financing of nuclear programmes and ballistic missiles.
Pompeo met with Ri on the edge of the UN General Assembly and later declared that he would visit Pyongyang again the following month to prepare a second summit.
Pompeo visited North Korea three times this year, but the last trip did not go well.
He went from Pyongyang in July stating that progress had been made, but a few hours after North Korea had accused him of having filed "gangster demands."
North Korea had committed itself during a meeting this month with Moon to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the USA had adopted "conform measures."
He said that Kim had explained to him that the "conformity measures" he wanted were security guarantees that Trump had committed to Singapore and actions towards normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has prompted all its students to sleep more in the attempt to counter the growing virile culture of studying for entire nights fueled by caffeine.
One university scholar found that college students number one in the world often have no idea of the basic concepts of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed the course, which he considers to be the first of this type in the USA.
He had the idea of starting the course after a conference that had given the impact of sleeplessness on learning.
"In the end a girl came to me and said to me, 'Why is this told only now, when I'm last year?'
He said that no one had ever told her anything about the importance of sleep, which surprised me very much," he told The Telegraph.
The course, given for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep-related habits can help academic and athletic performance as well as improve general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general director of health services at the university, said that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students suffered from a severe sleeplessness during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive activities.
In one section there is the image of a dormitory room, where students can select cups of coffee, tents, gymnastics shoes and books to be able to know the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is influenced by the lack of sleep, and the importance of a evening routine.
In another section, participants are explained how the long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know, just as you have the right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes," added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride linked to the "white night to study", still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students lead to a lack of sleep being a constantly growing problem.
Sleeping enough and with a good quality sleep should be the "secret weapon" of the students to fight stress, fatigue, anxiety, explained and should even serve to avoid fattening because the lack of sleep brings the brain in mode of inedia, making people constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student enrolled in the Faculty of Chemical and Physical Biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, after following one of his lessons last year in his first year at Harvard.
He explained that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course aimed at the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, will be to ask all graduates to follow a similar study programme before enrolling in this competitive institution.
Prof. Czeisler advised students to set a wake-up for when they need to go to bed, as well as for when they need to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can send the circadian rhythm to tilt, leading to sleeping problems.
