HIV/AIDS: China reports a 14% increase in new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of people with HIV and AIDS.
Over 820,000 people are affected by these diseases, according to sources of health authorities.
Some 40,000 new cases have been reported already in the second quarter of 2018.
The vast majority of new cases are due to sexual transmission, which marks a change from the past.
In some regions of China HIV has spread in the past as a result of infected blood transfusions.
But the number of people who have contracted HIV in this way has declined to almost zero, according to what the Chinese health authorities said during a conference in Yunnan province.
Year after year, however, the number of people with HIV and AIDS in China increased by 100,000 units.
Sexual transmission of HIV is an urgent problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is still widespread.
Due to the country's traditional values, some studies have estimated that 70-90% of men who have sex with other men eventually marry women.
Many of the transmissions of diseases are caused by inadequate protection during sexual intercourse within these relationships.
In 2003, the Chinese government promised universal access to anti-HIV drugs as part of its commitment to managing the problem.
