Syria says it is ready for the return of the refugees and is looking for help in rebuilding the country devastated by more than seven years of war.
In front of the United Nations General Assembly, the Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem stated that the country's conditions are improving.
"Today the situation on the territory is more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to recover the areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normality.
Now there are all the conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country that have had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that have affected their daily lives and their livelihood.
According to the United Nations estimate, more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million still living in Syria need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem stated that the Syrian regime will gladly accept assistance to rebuild the devastated country.
But he stressed that he will not accept any aid conditional on conditions or on the part of those countries that supported the insurrection.
